prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: MSXiiia_SG1_ra16
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Infrared selected sources: MSX A-D iiia sorted in Dec, RA = 16 1st 25 sources in RA range, in order of highest dec

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: The continuum flux entered for the sources are actually the flux in the MSX-A band for reference. The expected maser flux entered to allow validation of the proposal is unknown, but we expect at least 50 mJy for detections, which was used in, and is confirmed by our Cycle 2 detections (and a detection rate of well over 65%). The linewidths are anticipated to be approximately 7 km/s, and the polarization 0%. Whereas we do not intend to use Hanning smoothing during the observations, also because the masers can be much narrower than the nominal ~5-7km/s, when the data is smoothed to 5.6 km/s for detection purposes, this will result in an rms sensitivity better than 10 mJy/beam/channel and allow for more than 5 sigma detections in both narrow and nominal lines.

We ask for a spectral window with sufficient sensitivity and spectral resolution to detect typical SiO masers easily within the time on source. With one minute of observing (i.e., 40 sec on source), using the worst (5mm, 7th octile) water vapor and >30 receivers, assuming a 7 channel (5 km/s) detection requires a channel rms of about 10-15 mJy to detect a typical peak flux of 50 mJy at 10sigma in a 0.7 km/s channel. To set up the correlator we therefore choose 244 kHz non-Hanning smoothened frequency channels over 938 MHz dual polarization bandwidth for our primary SiO (2-1) v=1 line at 86.2 GHz. The total bandwidth (+- 1600 km/s) covers the full extent of probable Galactic line-of-sight velocities. The other sidebands are free to be chosen and we select the thermal 98.0 GHz J=2-1 (v=0) CS line for C/O ratio checking purposes. A third sideband is used to cover the SiO 2-1 (v=0) and simultaneously the (v=2) and 29SiO (v=0) lines; all these lines (and some other carbon lines) have been detected in our Cycle 2 program using the same setup.

The higher than normal data rate is a consequence of including two additional spectral windows covering the SiO (v=0) and (v=2) lines. If using this higher data rate would be a problem, we are willing to exclude these spectral windows but we note that this has not been an issue for the Cycle 2 observations. The advantage of including these lines is a more reliable detection and learning about the different stellar envelopes.

The imaging requirement is modest for these point-like maser sources; the limited uv-coverage and snapshot mode would actually help in resolving out any extended molecular emission not related to the stellar masers. For this we slightly prefer to use the more extended configurations, but the compact configurations will do very well too. We do not require high-quality images, just cubes that can be searched for point-like line emission. The MSX positional accuracy is about 2 arcseconds (with a beam of 18 arcseconds) so the angular resolution and positional accuracy is not an issue for either configuration.

The expected maser flux entered to allow validation of the proposal is unknown, but we expect at least 50 mJy for detections, which was used in, and is confirmed by our Cycle 2 detections (and a detection rate of well over 65%). The higher than normal data rate is a consequence of including two additional spectral windows covering the SiO (v=0) and (v=2) lines. If using this higher data rate would be a problem, we are willing to exclude these spectral windows but we note that this has not been an issue for the Cycle 2 observations. prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: A radio survey of red giant SiO sources in the inner Galaxy and Bulge is not hindered by extinction. Extremely accurate stellar velocities (<1 km/s) and positions are obtained with minimal observing time per source. Our aim to detect up to ~35,000 SiO maser sources will yield numbers comparable to optical surveys, but with the additional strength of a much more thorough coverage of the highly obscured inner Galaxy. The number of sources will be large enough to trace structures and minority populations and their velocity structure is to be compared with kinematic structures seen in molecular gas, complex orbit structure in the bar, or stellar streams resulting from recently infallen systems. Modeling of the bar and bulge dynamics will be done using this new kinematic information in the inner Galaxy region. Our survey will also yield sufficiently luminous SiO masers suitable for follow-up Galactic orbit and parallax determination using VLBI. We are successfully observing with our calibration scheme using the VLA at 43 GHz and ALMA Cycle2 pilot observations demonstrate excellent feasibility at 86 GHz. We here propose to expand the survey with ALMA in the Southern Bulge.
